            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 57-year-old Czech male of stocky build, standing approximately 178 cm tall and weighing 96 kg, with a visibly rounded abdomen and a slightly ruddy complexion. He works as a logistics supervisor at a freight company in Brno, spending long hours at a desk coordinating shipments and rarely finding time for physical activity. After work, he enjoys watching football, tinkering with his car in the garage, and socialising at the local pub over a beer with friends on weekends. He lives with his wife and their adult son in a small house on the outskirts of the city.\n\n{patientName} has been experiencing increasing fatigue, particularly in the afternoons [MEDDIALOG:E11.9:2], along with noticeable polyuria — needing to urinate frequently throughout the day and several times at night [SNOMED:E11.9]. He also reports persistent thirst and increased fluid intake (polydipsia) [SNOMED:E11.9], which he initially attributed to hot weather and salty pub food. He mentions occasional episodes of mild dizziness and general weakness in the afternoons [MEDDIALOG:E11.9:2]. His weight has been slowly increasing over the past few years despite no significant dietary change.\n\n{patientName} is a sociable, somewhat stubborn man who tends to downplay his symptoms and delayed seeking medical care for nearly two years after noticing the increased urination. His wife finally convinced him to attend his general practitioner after she noticed he was waking up multiple nights per week to use the bathroom. He does not smoke but drinks alcohol socially — typically 3–5 beers per week. His diet is heavy on Czech traditional food: pork, dumplings, and bread, with limited vegetables and fruit."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:aee9d21c-958c-46d0-abb4-85d52e95da4d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus approximately 8 months ago during a routine workplace health check, when fasting blood glucose was found to be elevated [PMID:34583764]. He has a positive family history of type 2 diabetes mellitus in his father [PMID:34583764]. He also has a longstanding history of borderline hypertension managed with lifestyle advice, and mildly elevated LDL cholesterol (136 mg/dL range) noted at his last blood draw [MEDDIALOG:E11.9:2]. He has no prior hospitalizations. He denies any episodes of hypoglycaemia or neuroglycopenic symptoms [PMID:34583764]. {patientName} has a sedentary occupation and low physical activity level. His BMI is approximately 30.3 kg/m², consistent with obesity class I. He is a non-smoker and moderate alcohol consumer. He has a documented allergy to penicillin manifesting as urticaria. No target organ damage has been identified to date, consistent with the diagnosis of T2DM without complications [PMID:34583764]. He underwent an oral glucose tolerance test at the time of diagnosis [PMID:29659364]."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
